	From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
	This article is about a class of molecules. For protein as a nutrient, see
	<a node_id=8a2fb7bf title="Protein (nutrient)">
		Protein (nutrient)
	. For other uses, see
	<a node_id=a2190e70 title="Protein (disambiguation)">
		Protein (disambiguation)
	.
	<a node_id=e4eedf5a>
	A representation of the 3D structure of the protein
	<a node_id=31466331 title="Myoglobin">
		myoglobin
	showing turquoise
	<a node_id=20f3ce06 title="Alpha helix">
		α-helices
	. This protein was the first to have its structure solved by
	<a node_id=72f74b3e title="X-ray crystallography">
		X-ray crystallography
	. Toward the right-center among the coils, a
	<a node_id=232cb242 title="Prosthetic group">
		prosthetic group
	called a
	<a node_id=7ddb8e48 title="Heme group">
		heme group
	(shown in gray) with a bound oxygen molecule (red).
	Proteins
	are large
	<a node_id=67e83b6f title="Biomolecule">
		biomolecules
	and
	<a node_id=2e6b7fd3 title="Macromolecule">
		macromolecules
	that comprise one or more long chains of
	<a node_id=3dc9d5ba title="Amino acid">
		amino acid
	<a node_id=33426e22 title="Residue (biochemistry)">
		residues
	. Proteins perform a vast array of functions within organisms, including
	<a node_id=48508ac5 title="Enzyme catalysis">
		catalysing metabolic reactions
	,
	<a node_id=47fc726a title="DNA replication">
		DNA replication
	,
	<a node_id=66ec04d2 title="Cell signaling">
		responding to stimuli
	, providing
	<a node_id=1b01a755 title="Cytoskeleton">
		structure to cells
	and
	<a node_id=a184fa4b title="">
		organisms
	, and
	<a node_id=e1992a93 title="Intracellular transport">
		transporting molecules
	from one location to another. Proteins differ from one another primarily in their sequence of amino acids, which is dictated by the
	<a node_id=d81ecc5b title="Nucleic acid sequence">
		nucleotide sequence
	of their
	<a node_id=8df35e25 title="Gene">
		genes
	, and which usually results in
	<a node_id=12c16522 title="Protein folding">
		protein folding
	into a specific
	<a node_id=ce045ae4 title="Protein structure">
		3D structure
	that determines its activity.
	A linear chain of amino acid residues is called a
	<a node_id=4a0942b4 title="Polypeptide">
		polypeptide
	. A protein contains at least one long polypeptide. Short polypeptides, containing less than 20–30 residues, are rarely considered to be proteins and are commonly called
	<a node_id=77e375a1 title="Peptide">
		peptides
	. The individual amino acid residues are bonded together by
	<a node_id=c292df7a title="Peptide bond">
		peptide bonds
	and adjacent amino acid residues. The
	<a node_id=41c88768 title="Protein primary structure">
		sequence
	of amino acid residues in a protein is defined by the
	<a node_id=e90d179e title="DNA sequencing">
		sequence
	of a gene, which is encoded in the
	<a node_id=0fd30785 title="Genetic code">
		genetic code
	. In general, the genetic code specifies 20 standard amino acids; but in certain organisms the genetic code can include
	<a node_id=7eb2c2af title="Selenocysteine">
		selenocysteine
	and—in certain
	<a node_id=d5f82d7a title="Archaea">
		archaea
	—
	<a node_id=b22d218a title="Pyrrolysine">
		pyrrolysine
	. Shortly after or even during synthesis, the residues in a protein are often chemically modified by
	<a node_id=a1a0ef6c title="Post-translational modification">
		post-translational modification
	, which alters the physical and chemical properties, folding, stability, activity, and ultimately, the function of the proteins. Some proteins have non-peptide groups attached, which can be called
	<a node_id=d679fdd7 title="Prosthetic group">
		prosthetic groups
	or
	<a node_id=fb623cf4 title="Cofactor (biochemistry)">
		cofactors
	. Proteins can work together to achieve a particular function, and they often associate to form stable
	<div node_id=fb2e6896>
		<a node_id=53b9351c>
			In molecular biology,
			fibrous proteins
			or
			scleroproteins
			are one of the three main classifications of protein structure. Fibrous proteins are made up of elongated or fibrous polypeptide chains which form filamentous and sheet-like structures. This kind of protein can be distinguished from globular protein by its low solubility in water. In contrast, globular proteins are spherical and generally soluble in water, performing dynamic functions like enzymatic activity or transport. Such proteins serve protective and structural roles by forming connective tissue, tendons, bone matrices, and muscle fiber.

	<a node_id=5aa777b9>
	A
	polymer
	(
	<a node_id=daa6eaea title="Help:IPA/English">
		/
		ˈ
		p
		ɒ
		l
		ɪ
		m

	<a node_id=27863057>

	) is a
	<a node_id=330a9d86 title="Chemical substance">
		substance
	or
	<a node_id=388dcced title="Material">
		material
	that consists of very large molecules, or
	<a node_id=03a242c1 title="Macromolecule">
		macromolecules
	, that are constituted by many
	<a node_id=3a38ddb4 title="Repeat unit">
		repeating subunits
	derived from one or more species of
	<a node_id=b6656bf3 title="Monomer">
		monomers
	.
	<a node_id=501caec7>
		6
	Due to their broad spectrum of properties,
	<a node_id=a91063b0>
		7
	both synthetic and natural polymers play essential and ubiquitous roles in everyday life.
	<a node_id=7da4baf2>
		8
	Polymers range from familiar
	<a node_id=b9dcbca9 title="Synthetic plastic">
		synthetic plastics
	such as
	<a node_id=2c396957 title="Polystyrene">
		polystyrene
	to natural
	<a node_id=14228aee title="Biopolymer">
		biopolymers
	such as
	<a node_id=475a845d title="DNA">
		DNA
	and
	<a node_id=67929ec5 title="">
		proteins
	that are fundamental to biological structure and function. Polymers, both natural and synthetic, are created via
	<a node_id=4c308190 title="Polymerization">
		polymerization
	of many small molecules, known as
	<a node_id=35d9b676 title="Monomer">
		monomers
	. Their consequently large
	<a node_id=6eaff0e6 title="Molecular mass">
		molecular mass
	, relative to
	<a node_id=7a4e430c title="Small molecule">
		small molecule
	<a node_id=e17b2b10 title="Compound (chemistry)">
		compounds
	, produces unique
	<a node_id=0845f731 title="Physical property">
		physical properties
	including
	<a node_id=90208d26 title="Toughness">
		toughness
	, high
	<a node_id=f82ae792 title="Rubber elasticity">
		elasticity
	,
	<a node_id=b923c1a1 title="Viscoelasticity">
		viscoelasticity
	, and a tendency to form
	<a node_id=f5a36062 title="Amorphous solid">
		amorphous
	and
	<a node_id=d8eff89d title="Crystallization of polymers">
		semicrystalline
	structures rather than
	<a node_id=9b6e0028 title="Crystal">
		crystals
	.
	Polymers are studied in the fields of
	<a node_id=13189213 title="Polymer science">
		polymer science
	(which includes
	<a node_id=344ec361 title="Polymer chemistry">
		polymer chemistry
	and
	<a node_id=04b630a5 title="Polymer physics">
		polymer physics
	),
	<a node_id=7e7177da title="Biophysics">
		biophysics
	and
	<a node_id=66d51d71 title="Materials science">
		materials science and engineering
	. Historically, products arising from the linkage of repeating units by
	<a node_id=84d3f590 title="Covalent">
		covalent
	<a node_id=669d08b0 title="Chemical bond">
		chemical bonds
	have been the primary focus of polymer science. An emerging important area now focuses on
	<a node_id=fa192c37 title="Supramolecular polymer">
		supramolecular polymers
	formed by
	<a node_id=bc617a15 title="Non-covalent interaction">
		non-covalent
	links.
	<a node_id=f9001b6e title="Polyisoprene">
		Polyisoprene
	of
	<a node_id=0a9a2096 title="Latex">
		latex
	<a node_id=45d8d79f title="Rubber">
		rubber
	is an example of a natural polymer, and the
	<a node_id=e1805d85 title="Polystyrene">
		polystyrene
	of
	<a node_id=292af970 title="Expanded polystyrene">
		styrofoam
	is an example of a synthetic polymer. In biological contexts, essentially all biological
	<a node_id=ae5013ae title="Macromolecule">
		macromolecules
	—i.e., proteins (polyamides),
	<a node_id=e7e83535 title="Nucleic acid">
		nucleic acids
	(polynucleotides), and
	<div node_id=98917307>
		<a node_id=617e616f>
		<a node_id=50802acd>
			Proteins
			are large biomolecules and macromolecules that comprise one or more long chains of amino acid residues. Proteins perform a vast array of functions within organisms, including catalysing metabolic reactions, DNA replication, responding to stimuli, providing structure to cells and organisms, and transporting molecules from one location to another. Proteins differ from one another primarily in their sequence of amino acids, which is dictated by the nucleotide sequence of their genes, and which usually results in protein folding into a specific 3D structure that determines its activity.

	From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
	Not to be confused with
	<a node_id=6cf104ec title="Plastic explosive">
		plastic explosive
	.
	Polymer-bonded explosives
	, also called
	PBX
	or
	plastic-bonded explosives
	, are
	<a node_id=ab0008cb title="Explosive">
		explosive
	materials in which explosive powder is bound together in a matrix using small quantities (typically 5–10% by weight) of a synthetic
	<a node_id=5a2f5be5 title="Polymer">
		polymer
	. PBXs are normally used for explosive materials that are not easily melted into a casting, or are otherwise difficult to form.
	PBX was first developed in 1952 at
	<a node_id=adef6cf0 title="Los Alamos National Laboratory">
		Los Alamos National Laboratory
	, as
	<a node_id=162d2974 title="RDX">
		RDX
	embedded in
	<a node_id=27aba1f9 title="Polystyrene">
		polystyrene
	with
	<a node_id=b054279a title="Bis(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate">
		diisooctyl phthalate
	(DEHP)
	<a node_id=0e6f5f73 title="Plasticizer">
		plasticizer
	.
	<a node_id=a81cd4a3 title="HMX">
		HMX
	compositions with
	<a node_id=aee07f14 title="Teflon">
		teflon
	-based binders were developed in 1960s and 1970s for
	<a node_id=73c95cd1 title="Shell (projectile)">
		gun shells
	and for
	<a node_id=9ac1d7ab title="Apollo Lunar Surface Experiments Package">
		Apollo Lunar Surface Experiments Package
	(ALSEP)
	<a node_id=d9a2cd2c title="Seismology">
		seismic
	experiments,
	<a node_id=c01e4146>
		[
		1
		]
	although the latter experiments are usually cited as using
	<a node_id=92df23f3 title="Hexanitrostilbene">

	(HNS).
	<a node_id=e9df9198>

	Potential advantages
	[
	<a node_id=33051dc8 title="Edit section: Potential advantages">

	]
	Polymer-bonded explosives have several potential advantages:
	If the polymer matrix is an
	<a node_id=c4be3347 title="Elastomer">
		elastomer
	(rubbery material), it tends to absorb shocks, making the PBX very insensitive to accidental detonation, and thus ideal for
	<a node_id=ab91a0d0 title="Insensitive munitions">
		insensitive munitions
	.
	Hard polymers can produce PBX that is very rigid and maintains a precise engineering shape even under severe stress.
	PBX powders can be pressed into a desired shape at room temperature; casting normally requires hazardous melting of the explosive. High pressure pressing can achieve density for the material very close to the theoretical crystal density of the base explosive material.
	Many PBXes are safe to machine; turning solid blocks into complex three-dimensional shapes. For example, a

High explosives (HE, or high-order explosives) are explosive materials that

High explosives detonate with an
<a node_id=e1c35c27 title="Explosive velocity">
	explosive velocity
of about 3–9 kilometres per second (9,800–29,500 ft/s). For instance, TNT has a detonation (burn) rate of approximately 6.9 km/s (22,600 feet per second), detonating cord of 6.7 km/s (22,000 feet per second), and C-4 about 8.0 km/s (26,000 feet per second).
High explosives tend to have the oxygen, carbon, and hydrogen contained in one organic molecule, and less sensitive explosives like
<a node_id=2629b17a title="ANFO">
	ANFO
are combinations of fuel (carbon and hydrogen fuel oil) and oxidizer (
<a node_id=09628ee2 title="Ammonium nitrate">
	ammonium nitrate
).
High explosives are normally employed in mining, demolition, and military applications.
High explosives can be divided into two explosive classes differentiated by
<a node_id=b9e23e3d title="Sensitivity (explosives)">
	sensitivity
:
<a node_id=3f5eb681>
	primary explosives
and
<a node_id=8acb21cf>
	secondary explosives
. Although tertiary explosives (such as ANFO at 3,200 m/s) can technically meet the explosive velocity definition, they are not considered high explosives in regulatory contexts.

Sure! Let’s zoom in on the specific example we’ve been using and unpack what “precursor” actually means in that context.

### What makes something a precursor?

In chemistry, a **precursor** is simply a starting material that gets transformed into another substance. During a synthesis, the precursor(s) react to form the product, often under the influence of heat, catalysts or other reagents. For example:

- **Glycerol → Nitroglycerin:** Glycerol reacts with nitric acid to form nitroglycerin. Glycerol is a precursor here.
- **Toluene → TNT:** Toluene is nitrated to form trinitrotoluene (TNT); toluene is the precursor.
- **Acetone + Hydrogen peroxide → TATP:** Acetone and hydrogen peroxide react (in the presence of an acid catalyst) to form acetone peroxide. Both acetone and hydrogen peroxide are precursors.

Being a precursor doesn’t imply any particular property other than “this molecule is one of the inputs”. Precursors are often simpler or more readily available compounds that can be purchased or produced easily.

### Why acetone and hydrogen peroxide?

On the acetone peroxide page, you saw two key reagents mentioned:

- **Acetone:** a small ketone that you might have in your home as nail polish remover. In the synthesis, the carbonyl group of acetone provides the carbon framework of the cyclic peroxide.
- **Hydrogen peroxide:** a common disinfectant. It supplies the oxygen atoms that form the peroxide linkages.

When these two compounds are mixed with an acid catalyst, their molecules combine and rearrange to make cyclic dimers, trimers, etc., of acetone peroxide. Because they’re consumed and incorporated into the final product, we call them precursors. The acid isn’t a precursor because it helps the reaction happen but isn’t used up.

In this context, **synthesis** means taking one or more simpler substances and chemically converting them into a more complex substance. It’s the chemistry equivalent of following a recipe: you start with ingredients (reactants), put them together under the right conditions (heat, catalysts, solvents), and end up with a new dish (the product). The reactants are consumed and their atoms are reorganised to form new bonds.

Let’s use our current example step by step:

1. **Ingredients (precursors):** You have acetone (CH₃COCH₃) and hydrogen peroxide (H₂O₂). Acetone provides a carbon “backbone”; hydrogen peroxide supplies oxygen–oxygen bonds (peroxide groups).

2. **Catalyst/conditions:** You add an acid such as sulfuric acid or hydrochloric acid. The acid doesn’t get used up, but it makes the reaction go faster by protonating the oxygen atoms and making acetone more reactive. You also keep the mixture cool, because this reaction is exothermic (releases heat) and can be hazardous if it runs away.

3. **Reaction (synthesis):** Under acidic conditions, hydrogen peroxide molecules add to the carbonyl group of acetone, and multiple acetone units link together through peroxide bridges. Depending on how many units join up, you get different cyclic “oligomers”: a dimer (two acetone units, known as diacetone diperoxide), a trimer (three units, TATP), or higher oligomers.

4. **Product:** The result is acetone peroxide – a cyclic organic peroxide. Its molecules are fundamentally different from the starting acetone and hydrogen peroxide. The carbonyl group of acetone is gone; its carbons are now joined by O–O bridges. The hydrogen peroxide molecules have been incorporated; their O–O bonds now connect the acetone fragments. Once formed, the acid can be washed away, and the product crystallises as a white powder.

A more familiar synthesis is water formation: 2 H₂ + O₂ → 2 H₂O. Hydrogen and oxygen gases (reactants) are ignited, their bonds break and new H–O bonds form, yielding liquid water (product). Similarly, aspirin is synthesised by reacting salicylic acid with acetic anhydride: the acetyl group from acetic anhydride attaches to the phenolic oxygen of salicylic acid, forming acetylsalicylic acid (aspirin) and releasing acetic acid.

Following those links can take you to other chemicals (e.g. sulfuric acid, hydrogen peroxide) or broader topics (e.g. organic peroxide, esterification). Understanding that synthesis is just “combining building blocks” helps you see why precursors matter: they’re the Lego bricks that get assembled into the target compound.
